        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5047.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Harrison William Weir</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">On CD’s interest in the grafted laburnum, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10043.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. J. Weir, 5 July 1875</ref> and n. 2. <hi rend="italic">Cytisus purpureus</hi> is a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Chamaecytisus purpureus</hi>, purple broom.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Crataegus oxyacantha</hi> is a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Crataegus monogyna</hi> (common or single-seeded hawthorn; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8808.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Christensen 1992</ref>). It has single white flowers. CD discussed a similar grafted hawthorn in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 377.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 18, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7247.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. J. Weir, 27 June 1870</ref>. <hi rend="italic">Hedera helix</hi> is the common or English ivy.</note>
        </div>        
            
